    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Plantago lanceolata are plantaginin, aucubin, quercetin, luteolin, and saponins, which are primarily responsible for its anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. Aucubin has been shown to inhibit the production of pro-inflammatory enzymes, while quercetin and luteolin have been found to have potent antioxidant activity, neutralizing free radicals and reducing oxidative stress. Plantaginin, a phenylethanoid glycoside, has been demonstrated to have anti-inflammatory and immunomodulatory effects, modulating the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines. Saponins, triterpenoid glycosides present in the plant, have been found to exhibit antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory activity, contributing to the wound-healing properties of Plantago lanceolata. The collective action of these constituents confers the plant its traditional use in treating various ailments, including inflammation, wound healing, and gastrointestinal issues.",
