    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Plantago lanceolata are derived from its leaves and aerial parts, which contain mucilages and flavonoids. Infusion is a liquid preparation made by steeping dried Plantago lanceolata leaves in hot water, used to treat coughs, colds and respiratory issues due to its expectorant properties. Tincture is a concentrated liquid preparation made by extracting the plant's active constituents with a solvent, used to treat digestive issues and skin problems due to its anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties. Tea is a preparation made by infusing dried Plantago lanceolata leaves in hot water, used to treat respiratory issues, coughs and colds due to its expectorant properties. Salve and ointment are topical preparations made by infusing Plantago lanceolata leaves in a carrier oil or fat, used to treat skin irritations, wounds and inflammation due to its anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties.",
